cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.SOC, cs.DS, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with identifying sub-communities and pivots in social networks, which falls under the scope of social network analysis. Therefore, cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of statistical and machine learning techniques, such as Karhunen-Loeve Transformation and probabilistic models, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.SI (Statistical Learning) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper deals with data reduction and dimensionality reduction, which could place it under cs.SD (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DS (Databases).
